ical evaluations in the light of on-going developments: Part I The Nature of Social Media sets up the conceptual groundwork as it explores key concept such as social media, participation, privacy/publicness. Part II Social Media Platforms focuses on the pragmatics of single platforms such as YouTube, Facebook. Part III Social Media and Discourse covers the micro-and macro-level organization of social media discourse, while Part IV Social Media and Identity reveals the multifarious ways in which users collectively (re-)construct aspects of their identities. Part V Social Media and Functions/Speech Acts surveys pragmatic studies on speech act functions such as disagreeing, complimenting, requesting. Each contribution provides a state-of-the-art review together with a critical evaluation of the existing research.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Aug 2020) 0aCommunication and technology. 0aLanguage and the Internet. 0aPragmatics. 0aSocial media. 0aSociolinguisticsxNetwork analysis. 4aPragmatics, Social Media, Internet, Facebook. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh1 aBublitz, Wolfram, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHoffmann, Christian, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2017z978311071954308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2017z9783110540550oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE ENGLISH 2017z978311062526408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Linguistics 2017z9783110547887oZDB-23-DSP0 cEPUBz97831104311170 cprintz978311043969440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311043107040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110431070423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cov